e submitted issues to the voters, why these votes have been won or lost - and ultimately why it matters. Uniquely, the book also examines the role of social media in referendum campaigns and make suggestions for improving the process of direct democracyWritten in a lucid style by one of the world’s leading experts on referendums, Democracy on demand is a timely reminder of the importance of democracy in our politics, offering new insights into how direct democracy can both improve our lives and at the same time strengthen our societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDirect democracy. 0aReferendum. 4aManchester Digital Textbooks. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  acitizens’ engagement.  acomparative politics.  ademocracy.  agood government.  agovernance.  ainitiatives.  aparticipation.  apopulism.  areferendums.  atrust.1 aQvortrup, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615896340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526158963423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526158963/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles